>
	<p>I'm Jonghyeok Park, a backend engineer.</p>

	<p>
		I've worked on systems that send large volumes of messages — things like Kakao alert-talk.
		Making sure a huge number of messages arrive on time without loss or delay is trickier than it
		sounds, and that's exactly the part I enjoy.
	</p>

	<p>
		I'm more curious about <em>why</em> code works than the fact that it runs, so I often dig into
		things I don't use at work. Once, just as a thought experiment, I designed how a ticketing server
		taking 100k QPS might stay alive — pushing Redis around in different ways. I've never run it in
		production, but it gave me a feel for where to start looking when things get big.
	</p>

	<p>
		I write down what I learn. On <a href="https://myvelop.tistory.com/">MYVELOP</a> I've published
		200+ posts on Spring, NestJS, Redis, Kubernetes, and CS fundamentals. Explaining things to others
		is how I end up learning the most.
	</p>

	<h2>Tech Stack</h2>
	<p>
		Java · Spring · NestJS / Redis · MySQL · RabbitMQ / Kubernetes · Docker · Jenkins · AWS
	</p>

